      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-solver-error",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver residuals converged to machine precision tolerance (1e-8) for all load steps. Contact nonlinearity handled with augmented Lagrangian method; force equilibrium residual <0.01% of applied load at each converged increment. Solver error assessed as negligible relative to other uncertainty sources."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-use-error",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by two independent analysts following a documented modeling protocol; results were cross-checked. Boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact pair definitions were reviewed by a third senior analyst. Discrepancies <0.3% between analysts, resolved by consensus. Use error controls documented in the modeling report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-form",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic isotropic material model for Ti-6Al-4V is appropriate for the sub-yield loading regime. Frictional contact (mu=0.3) at screw-rod and rod-block interfaces is physically motivated and consistent with published tribological data for titanium alloy interfaces. Large-deformation formulation (NLGEOM) enabled to capture geometric nonlinearity at 40 mm displacement. Model form assumptions reviewed against ASTM F1717 test geometry and found appropriate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-inputs",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E=114 GPa, nu=0.34 for Ti-6Al-4V) sourced from certified mill certificates for the specific lot used in testing. Geometric dimensions measured via CMM on five representative screws; mean and standard deviation reported. Torque-preload relationship for set screws characterized experimentally. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (n=1000) to quantify QoI sensitivity. All inputs traceable to primary measurements or certified reference data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-test-samples",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative components. Samples drawn from two independent lots; dimensional inspection confirmed conformance to design tolerances. Sample traceability documented via serial number log. Sample size sufficient to characterize inter-specimen variability for stiffness and yield force QoIs at 95% confidence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-test-conditions",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single standardized ASTM F1717 test condition (static compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead rate, room temperature, dry). Only one test condition evaluated; no variation in loading rate, temperature, or lubricant environment. This factor is below the required Gradation 2 level, consistent with the COU description noting this known limitation. The shortfall is accepted given that the COU is limited to the specific ASTM F1717 static protocol and the decision consequence is Medium."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-input-equiv",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, applied loads) were mapped directly to measured experimental parameters. CMM measurements of test specimens used to update nominal CAD geometry in the model. Applied force and displacement boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture configuration. Equivalency table prepared documenting each model input, its experimental counterpart, and the mapping uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-output-comparison",
      "rationale": "FEA-predicted stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement compared against experimental mean ± SD across N=11 constructs. Validation metric E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 9: all three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 (stiffness: 0.84, yield force: 1.21, force at 40 mm: 1.05). Percent differences: stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 3.1%, all within the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. Comparison results tabulated and traceable to raw experimental data and FEA output files."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
